    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.28"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">28</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        411 West 115th Street
                        New York City
                        September 11, 1929
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>My dear friend,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I greatly welcome and appreciate your letter, but deeply regret that you have been ill. Yet the Purpose will keep you well for your job; and I shall always add my own prayers to clear what little way they can.</p>
                
                <p>Peterson will be so happy in what you write. And,as you can well understand, your word of approval will mean much to him, and to me. With the established reputations of the book there will be no question, but there was a risk for him to do what he has done for me. So we shall both look forward to your article; and I shall treasure it among my sacred things. The <hi rend="underline">Evening Post</hi> gave a splendid review of the book last Saturday and had this to say about my sequence: "Another remarkable group is a series of ecclesiastical sonnets by Thomas <hi rend="caps">S.</hi> Jones, Jr., under the title of 'Christ in Briain'&#8212;&#8212; an original and colorful sequence with an unusual narrative flavor and a masterful flexibility of form." But there will be others who will not see the poems at that angle. But <hi rend="underline">you</hi> entirely understand and comprehend their purpose and what is behind them, and What has moved them. You are of my own kin, placed on the land where you are; but across country I can hail you. That is why your seal once placed openly on my work, will add to my force and further that purpose that is behind us both.</p>
                
                <p>I rejoice in all your good news: m<add>a</add>y your body be a clear and strong instrument for the work you have to do and which <hi rend="underline">will</hi> be done through you. May the great Powers of Light bless you and ever hold you in their keeping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Faithfully and affectionately</salute>
                
                    <signed>Thomas S. Jones, Jr.</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p>My dearest friend at school was a St. Louis boy &#8212;&#8212;now living among the Indians, <del/><add>or</add> was the last I heard of him; so you can understand how I shall treasure your words published in your present home town.&#8212; There is a scheme in it all, clearer and cle<del/>r<add>a</add>rer as the years go by. Of course,you have read Johan Jojer's <hi rend="underline">Great Hunger</hi>. I only found it this summer; <hi rend="underline">but I found it</hi>!</p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
